Note: Allocator Utility Functions
Process called "allocator_allocate" that takes allocator as Allocator and size as Integer and alignment as Integer returns Pointer:
    Try:
        Let pointer be allocator.allocate with size as size and alignment as alignment
        Set allocator.stats.total_allocated to allocator.stats.total_allocated plus size
        Set allocator.stats.current_usage to allocator.stats.current_usage plus size
        Set allocator.stats.peak_usage to max of allocator.stats.peak_usage and allocator.stats.current_usage
        Set allocator.stats.allocation_count to allocator.stats.allocation_count plus 1
        Return pointer
    Catch error:
        Set allocator.stats.error_count to allocator.stats.error_count plus 1
        If allocator.config.fallback_allocator is not None:
            Return allocator_allocate with allocator as allocator.config.fallback_allocator and size as size and alignment as alignment
        Return Pointer with:
            address as 0
            size as 0
            alignment as alignment
            allocator as allocator.name
            metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "allocator_deallocate" that takes allocator as Allocator and pointer as Pointer and size as Integer and alignment as Integer:
    Try:
        allocator.deallocate with pointer as pointer and size as size and alignment as alignment
        Set allocator.stats.total_freed to allocator.stats.total_freed plus size
        Set allocator.stats.current_usage to allocator.stats.current_usage minus size
        Set allocator.stats.deallocation_count to allocator.stats.deallocation_count plus 1
    Catch error:
        Set allocator.stats.error_count to allocator.stats.error_count plus 1
        If allocator.config.fallback_allocator is not None:
            allocator_deallocate with allocator as allocator.config.fallback_allocator and pointer as pointer and size as size and alignment as alignment

Process called "allocator_reset" that takes allocator as Allocator:
    If allocator.reset is not None:
        allocator.reset
    Set allocator.stats.current_usage to 0
    Set allocator.stats.peak_usage to 0
    Set allocator.stats.allocation_count to 0
    Set allocator.stats.deallocation_count to 0
    Set allocator.stats.error_count to 0

Note: Advanced Features
Process called "enable_thread_local_allocator" that takes allocator as Allocator returns Allocator:
    Set allocator.config.thread_local to true
    Return allocator

Process called "set_numa_node" that takes allocator as Allocator and node as Integer returns Allocator:
    Set allocator.config.numa_node to node
    Return allocator

Process called "enable_guard_pages" that takes allocator as Allocator returns Allocator:
    Set allocator.config.guard_pages to true
    Return allocator

Process called "enable_zero_memory" that takes allocator as Allocator returns Allocator:
    Set allocator.config.zero_memory to true
    Return allocator

Process called "set_fallback_allocator" that takes allocator as Allocator and fallback as Allocator returns Allocator:
    Set allocator.config.fallback_allocator to fallback
    Return allocator 

Note: Comprehensive Error Handling
Type OutOfMemoryError is Exception with:
    message as String
    allocator as String
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type BorrowingError is Exception with:
    message as String
    pointer as Pointer
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Process called "handle_allocation_error" that takes allocator as Allocator and size as Integer and alignment as Integer and error as Exception returns Pointer:
    Note: Centralized error handler for allocation failures
    Log error with allocator, size, alignment, and error.message
    If allocator.config.fallback_allocator is not None:
        Return allocator_allocate with allocator as allocator.config.fallback_allocator and size as size and alignment as alignment
    Throw OutOfMemoryError with message as error.message and allocator as allocator.name

Process called "handle_borrowing_error" that takes pointer as Pointer and error as Exception returns None:
    Note: Centralized error handler for borrowing failures
    Log error with pointer and error.message
    Throw BorrowingError with message as error.message and pointer as pointer

Note: Arena Allocator Implementation
Type ArenaAllocator is Dictionary with:
    start_position as Integer
    end_position as Integer
    current_position as Integer
    total_size as Integer
    config as AllocatorConfig
    id as String
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Process called "arena_allocate" that takes arena as ArenaAllocator and size as Integer and alignment as Integer returns Pointer:
    Note: Bump pointer allocation within arena bounds
    Let current_pos be arena.current_position
    Let aligned_pos be align_up(current_pos, alignment)
    Let end_pos be aligned_pos plus size
    If end_pos is greater than arena.end_position:
        If arena.config.fallback_allocator is not None:
            Return allocator_allocate with allocator as arena.config.fallback_allocator and size as size and alignment as alignment
        Otherwise:
            Throw OutOfMemoryError with message "Arena exhausted"
    Set arena.current_position to end_pos
    If arena.config.zero_memory:
        zero_memory with start as aligned_pos and size as size
    Return Pointer with:
        address as aligned_pos
        size as size
        alignment as alignment
        allocator as "arena"
        metadata as dictionary with "arena_id" as arena.id

Process called "arena_deallocate" that takes arena as ArenaAllocator and pointer as Pointer and size as Integer and alignment as Integer:
    Note: Arena allocators typically don't support individual deallocation
    Note: Memory is freed when entire arena is reset
    Return None

Process called "arena_reset" that takes arena as ArenaAllocator:
    Note: Reset arena to initial state, freeing all allocations
    Set arena.current_position to arena.start_position
    zero_memory with start as arena.start_position and size as arena.total_size

Note: Thread-Safe Pool Allocator
Type ThreadSafePoolAllocator is Dictionary with:
    pools as List[ThreadLocalPool]
    global_pool as Pool
    lock as AtomicSpinLock
    thread_count as AtomicInteger

Process called "thread_safe_pool_allocate" that takes pool as ThreadSafePoolAllocator and size as Integer returns Pointer:
    Let thread_id be get_current_thread_id()
    Let local_pool be pool.pools[thread_id]
    If local_pool is not None:
        Let pointer be try_allocate_from_local(local_pool, size)
        If pointer is not None:
            Return pointer
    Note: Fallback to global pool with locking
    With pool.lock:
        Return allocate_from_global(pool.global_pool, size)

Note: Lock-Free Stack Allocator
Type LockFreeStack is Dictionary with:
    top as AtomicPointer
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Process called "lockfree_stack_push" that takes stack as LockFreeStack and item as Any returns Boolean:
    Loop:
        Let top be atomic_load(stack.top)
        Set item.next to top
        If atomic_compare_exchange_weak(stack.top, top, item):
            Return true
        Note: Retry on failure 

Note: Pool Allocator Implementation
Type Pool is Dictionary with:
    free_list as List[Pointer]
    block_size as Integer
    total_blocks as Integer
    used_blocks as Integer
    config as AllocatorConfig
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Process called "pool_allocate" that takes pool as Pool and size as Integer and alignment as Integer returns Pointer:
    If pool.free_list is not empty:
        Let pointer be pop(pool.free_list)
        Set pool.used_blocks to pool.used_blocks plus 1
        Return pointer
    Otherwise:
        If pool.config.fallback_allocator is not None:
            Return allocator_allocate with allocator as pool.config.fallback_allocator and size as size and alignment as alignment
        Throw OutOfMemoryError with message "Pool exhausted"

Process called "pool_deallocate" that takes pool as Pool and pointer as Pointer and size as Integer and alignment as Integer:
    push(pool.free_list, pointer)
    Set pool.used_blocks to pool.used_blocks minus 1
    Return None

Process called "pool_reset" that takes pool as Pool:
    Set pool.free_list to all blocks in pool
    Set pool.used_blocks to 0
    Return None

Note: Slab Allocator Implementation
Type Slab is Dictionary with:
    slabs as List[List[Pointer]]
    slab_size as Integer
    config as AllocatorConfig
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Process called "slab_allocate" that takes slab as Slab and size as Integer and alignment as Integer returns Pointer:
    For each slab_list in slab.slabs:
        If slab_list is not empty:
            Return pop(slab_list)
    If slab.config.fallback_allocator is not None:
        Return allocator_allocate with allocator as slab.config.fallback_allocator and size as size and alignment as alignment
    Throw OutOfMemoryError with message "Slab exhausted"

Process called "slab_deallocate" that takes slab as Slab and pointer as Pointer and size as Integer and alignment as Integer:
    push(slab.slabs[find_slab_index(pointer)], pointer)
    Return None

Process called "slab_reset" that takes slab as Slab:
    For each slab_list in slab.slabs:
        refill slab_list
    Return None

Note: Stack Allocator Implementation
Type StackAllocator is Dictionary with:
    stack as List[Pointer]
    current_index as Integer
    config as AllocatorConfig
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Process called "stack_allocate" that takes stack as StackAllocator and size as Integer and alignment as Integer returns Pointer:
    If stack.current_index plus 1 is greater than length(stack.stack):
        If stack.config.fallback_allocator is not None:
            Return allocator_allocate with allocator as stack.config.fallback_allocator and size as size and alignment as alignment
        Throw OutOfMemoryError with message "Stack exhausted"
    Set stack.current_index to stack.current_index plus 1
    Return stack.stack[stack.current_index]

Process called "stack_deallocate" that takes stack as StackAllocator and pointer as Pointer and size as Integer and alignment as Integer:
    Set stack.current_index to stack.current_index minus 1
    Return None

Process called "stack_reset" that takes stack as StackAllocator:
    Set stack.current_index to 0
    Return None

Note: Region Allocator Implementation
Type RegionAllocator is Dictionary with:
    regions as List[Pointer]
    current_region as Integer
    config as AllocatorConfig
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Process called "region_allocate" that takes region as RegionAllocator and size as Integer and alignment as Integer returns Pointer:
    If region.current_region is less than length(region.regions):
        Let pointer be region.regions[region.current_region]
        Set region.current_region to region.current_region plus 1
        Return pointer
    If region.config.fallback_allocator is not None:
        Return allocator_allocate with allocator as region.config.fallback_allocator and size as size and alignment as alignment
    Throw OutOfMemoryError with message "Region exhausted"

Process called "region_deallocate" that takes region as RegionAllocator and pointer as Pointer and size as Integer and alignment as Integer:
    Note: Region allocators typically don't support individual deallocation
    Return None

Process called "region_reset" that takes region as RegionAllocator:
    Set region.current_region to 0
    Return None

Note: Hybrid Allocator Implementation
Type HybridAllocator is Dictionary with:
    allocators as List[Allocator]
    strategy as Function
    config as AllocatorConfig
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Process called "hybrid_allocate" that takes hybrid as HybridAllocator and size as Integer and alignment as Integer returns Pointer:
    Let selected_allocator be hybrid.strategy(hybrid.allocators, size, alignment)
    Return allocator_allocate(selected_allocator, size, alignment)

Process called "hybrid_deallocate" that takes hybrid as HybridAllocator and pointer as Pointer and size as Integer and alignment as Integer:
    Let selected_allocator be hybrid.strategy(hybrid.allocators, size, alignment)
    allocator_deallocate(selected_allocator, pointer, size, alignment)
    Return None

Process called "hybrid_reset" that takes hybrid as HybridAllocator:
    For each allocator in hybrid.allocators:
        allocator_reset(allocator)
    Return None

Note: Platform Memory Interface
Type PlatformMemory is Dictionary with:
    page_size as Integer
    virtual_memory_support as Boolean
    memory_mapping_support as Boolean
    huge_page_support as Boolean
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Process called "allocate_virtual_memory" that takes size as Integer and protection as MemoryProtection returns VirtualMemoryBlock:
    When running on "windows":
        Return windows_virtual_alloc(size, protection)
    When running on "linux":
        Return linux_mmap(size, protection)
    When running on "macos":
        Return macos_mmap(size, protection)

Note: Memory Mapping Support
Process called "map_file_to_memory" that takes filename as String and access as FileAccess returns MemoryMappedFile:
    Let file be open_file(filename, access)
    Let mapping be create_memory_mapping(file, access)
    Return MemoryMappedFile with file as file and mapping as mapping 

Note: Cache-Aware Allocation
Process called "cache_aware_allocate" that takes allocator as Allocator and size as Integer returns Pointer:
    Let cache_line_size be get_cpu_cache_line_size()
    Let alignment be max(allocator.config.alignment, cache_line_size)
    Let pointer be allocator_allocate(allocator, size, alignment)
    Note: Prefetch next cache lines for sequential access patterns
    If allocator.access_pattern is "sequential":
        prefetch_cache_lines(pointer.address plus size, 2)
    Return pointer

Note: Memory Bandwidth Optimization
Process called "optimize_memory_bandwidth" that takes operations as List[MemoryOperation] returns OptimizedPlan:
    Let plan be analyze_memory_access_patterns(operations)
    Let batched_ops be batch_operations_by_locality(operations, plan)
    Return OptimizedPlan with operations as batched_ops

Note: Generic Allocator Templates
Type AllocatorConcept[T] is Interface with:
    allocate as Function that takes size as Integer returns Pointer[T]
    deallocate as Function that takes pointer as Pointer[T] and size as Integer returns None
    construct as Function that takes pointer as Pointer[T] and value as T returns None
    destroy as Function that takes pointer as Pointer[T] returns None

Process called "create_typed_allocator"[T] that takes base_allocator as Allocator returns TypedAllocator[T]:
    Return TypedAllocator[T] with:
        base as base_allocator
        allocate as lambda size: typed_allocate[T](base_allocator, size)
        deallocate as lambda ptr, size: typed_deallocate[T](base_allocator, ptr, size)
        construct as lambda ptr, value: construct_at[T](ptr, value)
        destroy as lambda ptr: destroy_at[T](ptr)

Note: Simplified High-Level Interface
Process called "auto_memory" that takes block as CodeBlock returns Any:
    Note: Automatically choose optimal allocator and GC for code block
    Let profile be analyze_memory_patterns(block)
    Let allocator be auto_select_allocator(profile)
    Let gc be auto_select_gc(profile)
    With memory_context(allocator, gc):
        Return execute_block(block)

Let smart_memory be create_adaptive_memory_manager()
Note: Automatically tunes itself based on usage patterns 